    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-VII-2-sols">
        <title><m>\S VII.2</m>: Taylor Series</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Taylor Series </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We've seen that Taylor polynomials can approximate functions well, and in general, the higher
                            the degree, the better the approximation. This motivates the concept of a <term>Taylor series</term>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Definition: Taylor Series</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Given a function <m>f</m>, the <term>Taylor series of <m>f</m> centered at <m>x=0</m></term> is
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                T(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{f^{(n)}(0)}{n!} x^n
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Note that this is a function! That is, if you change the input <m>x</m> you get a new series. Our 
                            big question earlier with series was "Does it converge?". <m>T(x)</m> may converge for some 
                            <m>x</m>-values but not others.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Convergence of Taylor Series</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>T(x)</m> be a Taylor series. Then one of the following hold:
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>T(0)</m> converges but <m>T(x)</m> diverges for all other <m>x</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        There exists <m>R>0</m> such that <m>T(x)</m> converges if <m>|x| \lt R</m>, 
                                        and diverges if <m>|x| \gt R</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>T(x)</m> converges for all <m>x \in \R</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            The value <m>R</m> referenced above is called the <term>radius of convergence</term> for <m>T(x)</m>.
                        </p>
                       
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Taylor Series of Common Functions</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let's compute the Taylor series of some common functions.
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>f(x) = e^x</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>g(x) = \sin(x)</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>h(x) = \frac{1}{1-x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <me>T(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}</me>, <m>R = \infty</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <me>T(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}</me>, <m>R = \infty</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <me>T(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n</me>, <m>R = 1</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Note that with very few exceptions, if <m>f</m> has Taylor series <m>T(x)</m>, then <m>f(x) = T(x)</m>
                            for all <m>x</m> within the radius of convergence. Specifically for our functions above,
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>e^x =  \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}</m> for all <m>x</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sin(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!} </m> for all <m>x</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{1}{1-x} =\sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n </m> for <m>|x| \lt 1</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Properties of Taylor Series</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We can combine Taylor series of functions in meaningful ways to get Taylor series of new functions.
                            Let <m>f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n x^n</m> and <m>g(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_n x^n</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>(cf)(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty c a_n x^n</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>(f + g)(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (a_n + b_n) x^n</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>f'(x) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty n a_n x^{n-1} =\sum_{n=0}^\infty (n+1) a_{n+1} x^{n} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Example: A new Taylor series</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We know <me>
                                \sin(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            So
                            <me>
                                \cos(x) = \frac{d}{dx}(\sin(x)) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{d}{dx} \left((-1)^n \frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!} \right) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{2n}}{(2n)!}
                            </me>,
                            with <m>R=\infty</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: New Taylor series</title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Let's find the Taylor series for <m>f(x) = 2x^3e^{4x}</m>, given that we know
                            <me>
                                e^x = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write the Taylor series for <m>e^{4x}</m> using composition.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(4x)^n}{n!}</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write the Taylor series for <m>2e^{4x}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                 <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{2(4x)^n}{n!}</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                       
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write the Taylor series for <m>2x^3e^{4x}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{ 2^{2n+1}x^{n+3}}{n!}</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Example: New Taylor series</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \frac{1}{1+x} = \frac{1}{1- (-x)} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-x)^n = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n(x)^n
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Note also that 
                            <me>
                                \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{d}{dx} \left((-1)^n \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}\right) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n(x)^n
                            </me>,

                            and <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\ln(x) )=  \frac{1}{1+x}</m>. Since both <m>\ln(1+x)</m> and <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}</m> are <m>0</m>
                            when <m>x=0</m>, this suggests that
                            <me>
                                \ln(1+x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}
                            </me>,
                            and <m>R=1</m>.
                            
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

